# Git Commits

Remote: `https://github.com/aryelpanda/game-project.git`

## Version Control Model

Every **commit** is a restorable snapshot. Pushing sends those snapshots to GitHub, where the full history is kept forever (unless force-pushed).

- **Commit before push.** Never push uncommitted work as the only saved state.
- **One logical change per commit** when possible — makes reverting a single feature or fix easy.
- **Descriptive commit messages** — future you (or AI) must understand what changed and why.
- **Do not force-push** `main` unless the user explicitly requests it. Force-push erases remote history.

## Required Behavior

- **NEVER commit without explicit user permission.**
- After completing any code or doc change, **ask the user** whether they want a commit.
- Do not stage or commit proactively, even if changes look ready.
- Only commit when the user says yes (e.g. "commit", "yes, commit", "go ahead and commit").
- After a successful commit, **ask the user** whether they want to push.

## When the User Approves a Commit

1. Run `git status` and `git diff` to review changes.
2. Stage only relevant files (never secrets or debug artifacts).
3. Write a concise commit message focused on **why**, not just what.
4. Commit, then run `git status` to verify success.
5. Do **not** push unless the user explicitly asks.

## When the User Approves a Push

1. Confirm there is at least one new commit since the last push (`git log origin/main..HEAD`).
2. Push with SSL workaround if needed:
   `git -c http.sslBackend=schannel -c http.schannelCheckRevoke=false push`
3. Verify with `git status` (branch should be up to date with `origin/main`).

## Reverting (Reference)

| Goal | Command |
| ---- | ------- |
| Undo one commit safely (keeps history) | `git revert <commit-hash>` |
| Restore one file from an old commit | `git checkout <commit-hash> -- path/to/file` |
| View history | `git log --oneline` |
| Jump to old state locally (read-only) | `git checkout <commit-hash>` |

Never run `git reset --hard` or force-push without explicit user approval.

## Milestone Tags (Optional)

When the user approves a milestone (e.g. M3 complete), suggest tagging:

```
git tag -a v0.3-m3-horde -m "M3 horde run loop complete"
git push origin v0.3-m3-horde
```

Tags are permanent bookmarks for important versions.

## Forbidden

- Committing without permission.
- Pushing without permission.
- Amending or force-pushing without explicit request.
- Squashing or rewriting history on `main` without explicit request.
